{
  "text": "Part of the controversy surrounds the appropriate methods to be used in the study of faces [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In this article, we resurrected one traditional method used to approach the problem: We examined judgments of faces paired with situations. We relied on the face's normative preeminence over situations to help delimit the precise information the observer derives from the face. On our account, the face's normative preeminence is limited to quasi-physical features, pleasure, and arousal. So, both our account and those ofTomkins (1962) (1963) , [CITATION_4] , and [CITATION_5] predict facial dominance when face and situation are discrepant with regard to these matters. The interesting cases occur when face and situation are consistent in anticipated quasi-physical features, pleasure, and arousal, but discrepant on specific emotions.",
  "correct_citation": {
